    A delightful introduction, light & airy, flavorful and delicate. My only passing comment is that I was excited to experience the chive oil but was unable to detect it.

    - Amuse-Bouche 2/ Buckwheat Blini, CrÃ¨me FraÃ®che, Smoked salmon, Black Sea Osetra Caviar
    Unlike our experience at La Folie, the caviar that topped this lovely buttery & flaky blini was not fishy or repulsive, but tender and mild. I'm generally not a fan of smoked salmon, but this was done properly. A brilliant pastry with fresh flavors of the sea.

    - Seared Ahi Tuna with Avocado, Nori, Enoki Mushrooms & Lemon Soy Dressing
    The ahi tuna originally hadn't made my short list of items to order, but I was persuaded by the waiter to reconsider, and boy am I glad I did. It was absolutely delicious & fresh, with creamy avocado to balance the tangy vinegar dressing. The salty & crunchy sheet of dried seaweed sealed the deal.

    - Crispy Farm Egg with Grits, Royal Trumpet Mushrooms, FrisÃ©e & Pancetta
    Once again, wow. The egg was so delicately prepared, and the warm and hearty flavors of grits and buttery mushrooms made the perfect vehicle to deliver this goodness to my mouth.

    - Horseradish Crusted Salmon Medallion with Dilled Cucumbers & Mustard Sauce
    While I believe that salmon is genetically designed for eating raw, even I have to concede this this was done right, with tangy pickles and mustard to balance the palette. Not a tad fishy, just as it should be.

    - Seared Sea Scallops with Spring Onion Soubise, Melted Leeks & King Trumpet Mushrooms
    Wife said they were the best scallops she'd ever tried. I don't know that I would go that far, but they were pretty much perfect with that crispy seared top and melt-in-your-mouth soft center. Savory & creamy sauce and more of those buttery mushrooms.

    - Seared Filet of Beef with Cumin Potatoes, Swiss Chard, Tomato-Corn Relish & Basil Butter
    Filet mignon so juicy and tender that marbling wasn't needed. Lovely tomato corn combo, & potato chunks. There was nothing wrong with this dish, but we were starting to get full by this point and probably needed something more unique to re-energize us.

    - Roast Loin of Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Cipollini Onions & Wild Nettle SpÃ¤tzle
    I believe we've eaten a bison burger before at Fuddruckers, but we couldn't pass on the novelty of this dish. In retrospect, I wish we had ordered something else--not because it was bad, but because bison tastes like really lean beef (ie not as flavorful), and as we already had a beef dish from the set tasting menu, we should have diversified. Don't get me wrong, it was good, with those yummy mushrooms again, some sweet & mild cipollini onions, & buttery German spÃ¤tzle.

    - A Selection of Farmhouse & Artisanal Cheeses Presented Tableside
    We asked our snooty waiter to make a selection on our behalf--he chose for me Nuvola di Pecora (Clouds of Sheep), Central coast creamery, Harbison, & Rogue Creamery, and for her Sainte Maure Belgique, Napoleon, Etivaz, & Quadrello di Buffalo. I can't tell you much about the cheeses other than mine were very rich and hers were very light. One of mine (the Harbison I believe) tasted hauntingly like bacon, so I asked the waiter if there were any additives. When he said no, I quoted Napoleon Dynamite in his milk tasting competition, "It tastes like this cow stumbled into an onion patch." Our waiter wasn't amused. I love how Gary Danko serves the cheese with big sweet red grapes--this cuts through the richness quite expertly.

    - Chocolate Praline Parfait with Bourbon Sauce & Salted Caramel Ice Cream
    The gourmet version of a Klondike bar--perfectly round shaped & smooth, with an inside of frozen custard or frozen whipped cream. The salted caramel had a salty kick & provided the perfect contrast. So smooth.

    - Lemon Icebox Cake
    This semi frozen lemon mousse cake was presented for the birthday. Simple & delicious.

    - Mignardies & Pineapple souffle
    A collection of mini desserts, some chocolate-based, some lemon tarts, some coconut-y, some buttery. All good. And a pineapple souffle to eat as breakfast the next morning. These little details easily separate Gary Danko from the pack.
